titleStmt.title: It's In-Text and in Text: From Strings to URIs in TEI-to-RDF conversion

abstract.p: The way that data about the Humanities' central research area, the human record, is stored, retrieved, and visualized, shapes what digital-resource users can know about the past, and how they can use what they learn to inform the future. The Humanities are on the cusp of transformation as cultural data moves from quantities that can be comprehended at a human-scale (in, for example, digital monograph form, or in a single small database) to quantities that produce new knowledge through macro-visualization and computational inferencing – all provided that the academic community and beyond can develop pathways to continue to expand expertise in harnessing semantic web data. The Digital Humanities community and the GLAM sector have produced beautiful curated TEI, much of which serves individual projects well, but which has not been used beyond its home project. This paper reports on the attempts (following where others have tread) to create linked data from TEI resources. The process of creating linked data is far from straight forward, since TEI is by nature hierarchical, taking its meaning from the deep nesting of elements. Furthermore, the meaning the TEI elements are not always well-represented in existing ontologies. In addition to sharing our work to date, we are especially keen to solicit feedback from peers on the balance between granularity and generality in the representation of TEI-based information about people, places, time, and cultural production as linked data.

bibl.title: It's In-Text and in Text: From Strings to URIs in TEI-to-RDF conversion
bibl.author: Constance Crompton (University of Ottawa)

div.p: The way that data about the Humanities' central research area, the human record, is stored, retrieved, and visualized, shapes what digital-resource users can know about the past, and how they can use what they learn to inform the future. The Humanities are on the cusp of transformation as cultural data moves from quantities that can be comprehended at a human-scale (in, for example, digital monograph form,or in a single small database) to quantities that produce new knowledge through macro-visualization and computational inferencing–all provided that the academic community and beyond can develop pathways to continue to expand expertise in harnessing semantic web data (Lemus-Rojas and Odell; Hernández et al.; Maali et al.;Yu).

The Digital Humanities community and the GLAM sector have produced beautiful curated TEI, much of which serves individual projects well, but which has not been used beyond its home project. This paper reports on the attempts (following where others have tread) to create linked data from TEI resources. The process of creating linked data is far from straight forward, since TEI is by nature hierarchical, taking its meaning from the deep nesting of elements. Furthermore, the meaning the TEI elements are not always well-represented in existing ontologies.

This short paper reflects on our early attempts at representing TEI-based information about people, places, time, and cultural production as linked data. One of the strengths of the TEI is its reconfigurability1: it can be used and reused, restructured and transformed into other formats. Following in the footsteps of others in the TEI community who have transformed TEI into RDF, we too have been experimenting with best practices for created TEI-derived RDF (Ciotti and Tomasi). The challenge in this work comes from RDF's flatness relative to TEI-encoded documents. The meaning of TEI-encoded text comes from the hierarchical nature of the language. Any one element in TEI may be drawing its meaning from its relationship to a grandparent well up thetree (for example a persName appearing inside a listPerson inside the tei Header is more likely to be a canonical reference to a person than a persName whose parent is a paragraph). RDF, by comparison is fairly flat, and when working with a reasonably tight ontology, it offers usefully narrow sets of meaning for each element and attributevalue.

div.head: From TEI to RDF
div.p: We have started a sample set of TEI ographies to test how best to work out which ontologies make for best fit with TEI. These ographies comprise lists of people, events,and organizations, spanning 1800 to 1980. Our method for determining the meaning of any particular TEI element is two fold: first by reference to its definition and examples in the TEI guidelines, and second, from its local use in one of a our sample datasets2.We then weighed that meaning against subjects and objects from a range of ontologies,including Schema.org, the DBPedia ontology, DOLCE, TIME, DC, Bibframe, FRBRoo,BIBO, CIDOC-CRM, FOAF, CWRC, Open Annotation, GeoNames, or W3C Provenance. We used a number a criteria to winnow this list down. The three most important were1) how close the entities defined in that ontology matched canonical and project-specificuse of the TEI elements, 2) how widely the ontology is used, and 3) how well it was already represented in our attempt at TEI element to RDF entity matching. We want to reduce down to as few (and most popular or best supported) ontologies as possible.

The early front runners were:
DOLCE for its close match to TEI concepts and uptake in the Wikimediacommunity
The CWRC Ontology for its TEI-like granularity and intuitive articulation ofHumanities concepts
CIDOC-CRM for its capaciousness and broad uptake in the galleries andmuseums sectors of the GLAM community
Schema.org for its broad uptake, albeit in commercial circles, and its intuitive, ifover simplistic, articulation of entity types and their relationships
BIBFRAMEfor its granularity and for its uptake as a replacement for MARC inthe library sector

These frontrunners are not without their challenges, and we are particularlykeen to getfeedback from the ADHO LOD-SIG members on our next steps. Forexample, in the past few months we have decided to set DOLCE aside, because, eventhough it is used in Wikimedia circles it is not actively maintained. Our inclination totake up Schema.org ontology is also fraught. On the one hand, because it accepts stringsrather than uris for a number of its values, Schema does not force users to createparticularly high quality (by which we mean interlinked) linked data, relative to otherontologies that demand uris. That said, its string-friendliness does make it a goodmatch for the TEI, which, after all, is a text encoding language. While the TEI includes mechanisms for creating highly interlinked documents, we have found that the use ofpointing attributes to connect to existing authorities was not as wide spread in oursample TEI as we had hoped. In its string-friendliness, Schema is a good fit for TEI-encoded documents, which do not always have xml:ids from which to mint uris or point via @sameAs to existing authorities.

While we will not discuss our conversion strategies in depth here, we have had considerable success with, as one might expect, XSLT, but also with XTriples is generic API-backed webservice for creating RDF statements from XML resources developed by Academy of Sciences and Literature and the Institute for Spatial Information and Surveying Technology in Mainz. Xtriples has users create a configuration XML document that describes what to take from the input document (in our case TEI), and what should be included in the resulting RDF output. It is a wonderful user-friendly resource, but it does not include validation against the existing ontology or complex XPath, to date its only limitations.

div.head: Too Stringy? Look it Up
div.p: While Schema's string-friendliness might superficially make a good fit for TEI conversion, our goal is to create linked data, rather than to create relatively low-quality Schema-based RDF out of TEI (after all, TEI documents tend to be quite rich, but much of that richness is lost in the creation of a Schema-based representation in the text. The trade off in richness, however, is not compensated by the quality of the resulting RDF).We expect that being able to drawn on Wikidata entities will be the best way to create high-quality linked data from TEI that only has internal project links.

While Schema's string-friendliness might superficially make a good fit for TEI conversion, our goal is to create linked data, rather than to create relatively low-quality Schema-based RDF out of TEI (after all, TEI documents tend to be quite rich, but much of that richness is lost in the creation of a Schema-based representation in the text. The trade off in richness, however, is not compensated by the quality of the resulting RDF).We expect that being able to drawn on Wikidata entities will be the best way to create high-quality linked data from TEI that only has internal project links. We would like to turn to Wikidata, whose ontologies are not necessarily appropriate for TEI-related work, but whose entity lists are huge and whose individual entities are highly connected, linking out, for example to VIAF, ISNI, SNAC, IMDb, the ODNB, Canadiana and more. Wikidata content is readily accessible via query and API, which means that any number of web services can be built on top of it. Furthermore it records provenancial data and so offers avenues for reification, correction, and recording disagreements. We expect that the solution the challenge of converting string-filled TEI will be in the creation of and integration with existing entitiy look-up tools, like CWRC-Writer's look-ups for entity names in VIAF, Wikidata, Geonames and more. We are, as we consider the Wikidata, route confronted by a further challenge: even though Wikidata is capacious, it is built on (but happily not limited to)entities who meet Wikipedia's notability criteria. Much of the value of TEI-encoding projects is their work to uncover information about people,places, and organizations that have been understudied, who are interesting edge cases,and who in other ways represent untread ground. We worry the reliance on Wikidata will further reify the already canonized rather than promoting the underrepresented people, places, and organizations that are finally getting scholarly attention through digital humanities projects. We will look forward to feedback from the LOD-SIG on these issues, best practices, and next steps.
